        <td  bgcolor="#FFFFFF" width="100%" valign="top"><font color="#08599C">
         <b>Author:&nbsp;<a class=doctorLink href="mailto:&#108;&#111;&#118;&#101;&#117;&#98;&#97;&#98;&#101;&#48;&#48;&#55;&#105;&#110;&#64;&#121;&#97;&#104;&#111;&#111;&#46;&#99;&#111;&#109;?subject=RE: Time for a schedule change?">Abhi(India)</a> </b><br>
         <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
           <tr>
             <td><font color="#08599C"><b>Date:&nbsp;</b></font></td>
             <td><DIV DIR="ltr"><font color="#08599C"><b>02-11-2005 21:00</b></font></DIV></td>
           </tr>
         </table>
         <br>
      A lot of players criticize the tennis season as being too long & they complain about there being no off-season. However, the tournaments made mandatory by the ATP for the top-ranked players to compete in are only the 4 grand slams & the 9 TMS events. The year ending TMC is too prestigious for the qualifying players to miss. So, we’re talking about 14 tournaments per year. You don’t have to play all 5 of the other tournaments that are added to your ranking. Each Davis Cup round is played over Fri, Sat, Sun which should not be too taxing for the players since they are representing their country and it is an honour for them to do so.<br />
<br />
If a player chooses to play only the major tournaments, then his schedule would be:<br />
<br />
Month – Number of tournaments - Tournament<br />
Jan – 1 - Australian Open<br />
Feb – 0 - No tournament<br />
Mar – 2 - Indian Wells TMS, Miami TMS<br />
Apr – 1 – Monte Carlo TMS<br />
May – 3 – Rome TMS, Hamburg TMS, French Open<br />
June – 1- Wimbledon<br />
July – 0 - No tournament<br />
Aug – 2 - Canada TMS, Cincinnati TMS<br />
Sep – 1 – US Open<br />
Oct – 2 – Madrid TMS, Paris TMS<br />
Nov – 1- TMC<br />
Dec – 0 - No tournament<br />
<br />
<br />
Perhaps the Aussie Open can be shifted to March & the 2 TMS events that are currently being played in March can be shifted to Feb. Thus, a player would have 2 months off. (Dec & Jan)<br />
<br />
I don’t understand the lack of uniformity in the TMS events. Indian Wells & Miami are draws of 96. Madrid & Paris are draws of 48. The other TMS events are draws of 64. All TMS events should have draws of 48. This is important because some TMS events are back to back. (Rome/Hamburg & Canada/Cincy) If a player reaches the final rounds of an event, he needs the extra day to recuperate before playing his 1st match in the next tournament.<br />
<br />
Lets analyse the Number of ‘Other tournaments’ played of some top ranked players to make up their ‘Best 5 Other tournaments’. (as on 31/10/05)<br />
Federer 5. (Perfect)<br />
Nadal 11 !!<br />
Roddick 7.<br />
Hewitt & Safin have been injured this year. Last year, they played 6 & 9 respectively.<br />
Coria 9.<br />
Davydenko 16 !!<br />
Gaudio 11 !!<br />
Nalbandian 7.<br />
Ljubicic 10 !!</font></tt><p>
    </td>
  </tr>
</table></td>
</tr>

